1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O Nf6 { This natural move is less common than 4...a6 nowadays because White is allowed to comfortably secure f1 for his bishop. } 5. Re1 a6 6. Bf1 b6 { The most precise way of development - the early fianchetto prevents White from seizing centre with ..c2-c3 and d2-d4. } 7. c3 ( { The most common continuations are } 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bb7 9. c4 ) ( { and } 7. c4 Bb7 8. Nc3 e6 9. d4 { and they both lead to a long Hedgehog struggle. Although White's results are usually decent there, I prefer to opt for other type of positions. } ) 7... Bb7 8. d3 { This is practically forced. White intends to first mobilize his forces and push d3-d4 at the proper moment. } 8... e6 { The most solid choice. } ( { The alternative way of development is } 8... g6 9. Nbd2 { White stregntens e4 and prepares ..d3-d4. } 9... Bg7 10. d4 O-O { For some reason, this natural move was only seen in a couple of high-level games so far. } ( { In the event of } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O 12. a4 e5 ( { After } 12... Rc8 13. b3 Qc7 14. Ba3 { Black's position is rather crumped in view of White's full control over the centre. } ) 13. d5 { White has an excellent position a la KID. A likely continuation is } 13... a5 { The best Black can do is secure c5 for the knight } 14. Nb1 $1 { An effective regroup. } 14... Nc5 15. Nc3 Ne8 16. Rb1 { White's play on the queenside with b2-b4 is lasting fast. } ) 11. e5 { The most aggressive choice. } 11... Nd5 ( { After } 11... dxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. e6 { Black suffers from serious damage to kingside pawn chain. } 13... fxe6 14. Ng5 Nc7 15. Qg4 { White superior pawn structure and decent attacking prospects. } ) 12. c4 { White is naturally interested in blocking the opponent's light-squared bishop and gaining more space. } 12... Nc7 13. exd6 exd6 14. d5 b5 { Black has to play this move in order to free himself. } 15. Ne4 bxc4 16. Bg5 $1 { An important intermediate move that interrupts the opponent's piece coordination. } 16... Nf6 17. Bxc4 { A complex struggle a-la Benko is ahead, but I like White's chances because of superiority in space and active g5-bishop. } ) ( { Too risky is } 8... c4 9. dxc4 Nxe4 { Balck grabs the central pawn, but it costs him opening file against the king. } 10. Nbd2 Nef6 { This was Sidhant, M - Akshat, K Noida 2016 Hree the most energetic was } 11. a4 $14 e6 12. a5 Be7 13. Nb3 { White has a powerful initiative on the queenside. The a6-pawn is very vulnerable. } ) ( 8... e5 { was played by many strong players. Still, it is weaker: } 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. d4 O-O ( { After } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Nxd4 O-O 13. Nf5 { White had both superior pawn structure and promising attacking prospects in Jakovenko, D - Inarkiev,E Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 } ) 11. d5 Ne8 12. Nc4 g6 13. Bh6 Ng7 { This position a-la KID took place in Kayumov, S - Ashwin, J Abu Dhabi 2006 Here I mostly like the energetic } 14. a4 f5 15. Nfd2 Rf7 16. b4 { White takes the upper hand on the queenside, while Black's counterplay on the kingside is questionable because of crumped pieces. } ) 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. d4 O-O ( 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O 12. a4 { transposes to 10...0-0. } ) 11. a4 { A decent move. Black is prevented from playing ...b6-b5. Also, White can activate his rook with ..Ra3 in some cases. } 11... cxd4 ( 11... d5 { isn't really well-timed: } 12. e5 Ne4 13. Bd3 { Black has an inferior version of French with blocked light-squared bishop. } ) ( { The attempt to maintain the tension by means of } 11... Qc7 { can be well met by } 12. d5 $1 exd5 13. exd5 Rfe8 14. c4 $14 { Black has no compensation for a lack of space. } ) 12. cxd4 Rc8 13. Bd3 { White covers c2 and strengthens e4. } 13... e5 { Black is reasonably aiming to stabilize the centre. } ( { Weaker is } 13... Qc7 14. Nf1 Rfe8 15. Ng3 $14 { White has reached a harmonious attacking setup, while Black's active play is questionable. Fedorchuk, S - Gharamian, T Paris 2011 } ) 14. d5 Nh5 ( 14... Nc5 $5 15. Bc2 a5 { is worth attention. Even so, } 16. Ra3 Ba6 17. Nb1 Qd7 18. Nc3 { looks comfortable for White, who has superiority in centre and potential b5-outpost for the knight. } ) 15. Nc4 Nc5 { This position was reached in Kovalev, V - Bosiocic, M Spilimbergo 2019 Now the energetic } 16. a5 $14 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 b5 ( 17... bxa5 18. Nxa5 { is hardly more attractive for Black. } ) 18. Nb6 Rc7 19. Be3 { would have offered White clear prospects on the c-file due to strong b6-knight. } *[Event "?"]
