1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O Nf6 5. Re1 a6 ( 5... e5 { is very risky from a strategic point of view as it leaves the dark-squared bishop blocked and weakened d5. Still, it was played by many strong players. } 6. c3 Be7 7. d4 O-O { In this position White can choose between few natural continuations, when I mostly like the rare } 8. Bf1 $5 { A flexible continuation. The bishop did its job on b5. From now one of White's key ideas is to capture on e5 and then occupy d5 by means of c4, Nc3. } 8... a6 ( { Hardly better is } 8... Qc7 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. c4 Be6 12. Nc3 $14 ) 9. dxe5 { The most conceptual. } 9... dxe5 ( { Another possible scenario is } 9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. c4 { White has a small but stable positional advantage due to access to d5. } ) 10. c4 Nb8 { This move tell by itself - Black is desperately trying to transfer his knight on d4. } 11. Qxd8 Bxd8 12. Nxe5 { Black didn't have proper compensation for the pawn in Bologan, V - Bortnyk, O Chess.com INT 2020 } ) ( { Too passive is } 5... e6 6. c3 Be7 ( 6... a6 7. Bf1 { transposes to 5... a6. } ) 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 { White has superior development and a strong pawn centre. } ) ( 5... g6 { This move also allows White to comfortably build a pawn centre. } 6. c3 Bg7 7. d4 O-O 8. d5 a6 9. Bf1 Re8 { Black is trying to challenge the centre with e7-e6. } ( { After } 9... b6 10. a4 Qc7 11. h3 { Black's pieces were too crumped in Di Berardino, D - Quintiliano Pinto, R Florianopolis 2016 } ) 10. a4 { White secures c4 for his bishop and radically prevents ...b7-b5. } 10... e6 11. dxe6 Rxe6 12. Bc4 { An important tactical resource. White seizes initiative because } 12... Rxe4 $6 { runs into } 13. Bxf7+ { , and the bishop is untouchable in view of 14. Ng5+. } ) 6. Bf1 e6 { This is Black's second choice after 6...b6. } ( 6... g6 7. c3 Ne5 { This somewhat artificial maneuver is aimed to partly solve Black's space issues by exchanging pieces. } ( 7... Bg7 8. d4 O-O 9. d5 { transposes to 5...a6. } ) 8. d4 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 { On the downside, Black's development is delayed, and it allows White to quickly extend initiative in centre with e4-e5. } 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Bg7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. e5 { Black was in big trouble in Speelman, J - Anand, V Geneve 1996 } ) ( 6... Ne5 { is a similar attempt to equalize, in similar to Speelman-Anand. } 7. Nxe5 { The straightforward reaction. After all this change of pawn structure is favorable for White. } ( 7. c3 $5 { is another promising option. } ) 7... dxe5 8. a4 Bg4 ( 8... b6 9. Na3 Bb7 { , as in Iordachescu, V - Vasiesiu, D Bucharest 1997 runs into } 10. Nc4 $14 Nd7 11. c3 e6 12. d4 $36 { Black struggles to complete development. } ) 9. Be2 Bd7 10. b3 { White opts for a harmonious way of development. It will put pressure on e5. } 10... Bc6 11. Bb2 Nd7 12. Na3 g6 { This was Sedina, E - Fuchs, J Ruzomberok 2014 Here I like the accurate } 13. Bd3 $14 Bg7 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Bc3 e6 16. a5 $14 { , fixing favorable pawn structure on the queenside. } ) ( 6... b5 $6 { This is nearly the most ambitious continuation. Black goes for a traditional extension in order to place the bishop on b7 and attack White's central pawn. However, it isn't well-timed: Blacl's pieces are poorly developed for such committing actions. } 7. d4 { One of the few ways of opening files. White's development advantage starts to tell. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bb7 ( { After } 8... e5 9. Nf5 Nc5 10. Bg5 Ncxe4 11. Nxg7+ Bxg7 12. Rxe4 $36 { Black found himself overextended in Manik, M - Mladek, R Pardubice 2018 } ) 9. c4 $1 { The most energetic conitunation. } 9... bxc4 ( { Also after } 9... b4 10. a3 bxa3 11. Rxa3 { Black faces serious problems with development and ruined queenside. } ) 10. Bxc4 e6 11. Nc3 { As it often happens in Sicilian, Black should deal with various sacrificial ideas such as Bxe6, Nxe6 or Nd5. } 11... Rc8 ( { After } 11... Be7 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Nxe6 { White gets 3 pawns for the piece and powerful attack. } ) 12. Qe2 Nc5 13. b4 Ncxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxa6 { Black was on the verge of collapse because of poor development. Shyam, S - Nielsen, P Dubai 2014 } ) ( 6... e5 { has no independent value: } 7. c3 Be7 8. d4 O-O { transposes to 5...e5. } ) 7. c3 { Of course, now White feels more comfortable with this move - Black is unable to immediately attack e4. } 7... Be7 ( { The only reasonable alternative is } 7... b5 8. d4 Bb7 9. e5 dxe5 ( 9... Nd5 10. dxc5 { leads to the same, as } 10... Nxc5 $6 11. b4 Nd7 12. a4 { is too dangerous for Black, whose queenside is totally ruined. } ) 10. dxe5 Nd5 11. a4 { There is no comfortable way to cover b5. } 11... c4 ( { After } 11... b4 12. a5 Qc7 13. Qc2 Be7 14. Nbd2 { White has excellent attacking prospects as Black's pieces are well-restricted. } ) 12. Nd4 $1 { white activates the knight and vacates g4 for the queen. } 12... Qb6 13. Qg4 { Black's bishop is now tied with defending g7. } 13... h5 14. Qg5 h4 15. h3 { A complex struggle is ahead when White's practical task is much easier because Black's king is stuck in centre. } ) 8. d4 cxd4 ( { In the event of } 8... O-O { White can push in centre with no delay: } 9. e5 dxe5 ( { After } 9... Nd5 10. c4 Nb4 11. a3 Nc6 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nc3 { White has the better piece coordination and promising play on the queenside with b2-b4 to follow. } ) 10. dxe5 Nd5 11. c4 { depriving Black's knight of an excellent central spot. } 11... Nb4 12. Nc3 b6 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Ne4 $14 { Black clearly lacks harmony. Arribas Robaina,M - Pina Vega,S Guatemala City 2005 } ) 9. cxd4 b5 10. Bd3 { The bishop is well-placed on d3, where is supports e4 and can be used for attacking actions with e4-e5 in the long run. } 10... O-O 11. Nbd2 { White moves the knight towards g3 in analogy to Ruy Lopez paths. } 11... Bb7 12. Nf1 Qc7 13. Ng3 Rfe8 14. Bd2 { White had the better position due to the powerful centre in Shibaev, V - Gryzov,A Riazan 2011 } *[Event "?"]
