1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Be2 g6 { This is Black's main alternative to 5...Ngf6. The immediate fianchetto makes it possible for Black to place the knight on e7 in the long run. } 6. d4 $1 { This is the only way to claim some drawbacks of Black's last move. } ( { After } 6. c3 Ngf6 $1 7. Qc2 Qc7 { Black has no problems at all. } ) 6... cxd4 ( { Dubious is } 6... Bg7 $6 7. c3 Qc7 8. Re1 { White has a clear advantage due to superiority in centre. } ) 7. Qxd4 Ngf6 ( { After } 7... e5 8. Qe3 Ngf6 9. c4 { White has clear structural superiority. } ) 8. Rd1 Bg7 9. Nc3 { White reasonably opts for q quick development. The favorable opposition on the d-file makes the potential e4-e5 advance very promising. } 9... O-O ( { The only adequate alternative is } 9... Qc7 10. Nd5 Qd8 ( { Too greedy is } 10... Qxc2 $2 11. Be3 { , and then Black will most likely lose e7 in inferior redaction - White's development advantage is threatening here. } ) 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Qe3 Nxd5 13. exd5 { , but then White has clear structural superiority. Wen,Y - Xu,J Nanjing 2023 } ) 10. e5 $1 Nh5 { The most challenging response. The pinned e5-pawn is about to fall, so White has to play very energetically. } ( { After } 10... dxe5 11. Nxe5 { White doesn't fear of pin on the long diagonal because the pin of d7-knight prevails. } 11... Ne8 ( { After } 11... Qa5 12. Nc4 Qf5 13. Ne3 Qa5 14. Bd2 { Black struggles to develop his c8-bishop. Fedoseev,V - Rathanvel,V Chess.com INT 2020 } ) ( { Equally possible is } 11... Qc7 12. Nc4 Re8 13. a4 b6 14. Qf4 { white's pieces were much more active in Guo, A - Hong, A Saint Louis 2023 } ) 12. Bf4 Nd6 13. Qe3 { Black is practically forced to capture on e5. } 13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. Qxe5 Be6 16. Ne4 { White has a slight, but long-lasting advantage due to more active pieces. Sethuraman, S - Bharath, S chess24.com INT 2022 } ) ( 10... Nxe5 $5 { is an interesting tactical attempt to solve all the issues. } 11. Nxe5 Nd7 12. Nxf7 Bxd4 $1 { Only this can be justification of Black's previous play. } ( 12... Rxf7 13. Qh4 { leaves Black with a poor pawn structure. } ) 13. Nxd8 Bxf2+ 14. Kh1 Rxd8 15. Bc4+ Kg7 16. Rf1 Ne5 ( { After } 16... Rf8 17. Bg5 Bd4 18. Bxe7 { White regains the pawn and retains the merits of his setup. } ) 17. Rxf2 Nxc4 18. Bg5 Bf5 19. Bxe7 { Black's king is still in danger, although queens are not on the board. Gavrilescu,D - Cubas,J Chennai 2022 } ) 11. Qh4 { Black should choose way of capturing e5. } 11... dxe5 ( { Worth mentioning is } 11... Nxe5 $5 12. Nxe5 Bf6 $1 { A decent intermediate move. } ( { After } 12... Bxe5 $2 13. Bxh5 gxh5 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Nd5 { Black's king is too exposed, so White is nearly winning. } ) 13. Bg5 Bxg5 14. Qxg5 f6 { Black manages to regain the piece in a comfortable situation. However, it costs him to weaken the king. } 15. Qh6 fxe5 16. Ne4 { This position isn't so clear, but White's practical task seems easier because of Black's exposed king. } ) 12. Bg5 Bf6 ( { Very risky is } 12... f6 { , although it was mainly played by strong players } 13. Be3 e6 { Black prevents ..Rd5, but White has many other promising options. } ( 13... Kh8 $2 { , as in Nasuta,G - Navara,D Warsaw 2020 is well met by } 14. g3 $14 { Black's pieces are really stuck now. } 14... b6 15. Nd5 Rb8 16. g4 { White regains the pawn and achieves nearly the winning position. } ) 14. Rd6 { White dominates on the entire board. } 14... Nf4 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. Bc4 { Black was in big trouble in Vovk, A - Asis Gargatagli, H La Massana 2015 } ) ( { Too passive is } 12... Nhf6 13. Nxe5 Qc7 14. Ng4 $36 { White regains a pawn, and Black's pieces remain rather cramped. } ) 13. a4 { White maintains the tension by preventing ...b7-b5. It isn't easy for Black to find vital moves. } 13... Kg7 14. Bxf6+ Nhxf6 ( { After } 14... exf6 15. g3 $1 Kg8 16. Rd2 { Black's pieces are paralyzed. His extra pawn doesn't really tell. } ) 15. Nxe5 Qc7 16. Nc4 { White will next double the rooks with ..Rd4,Rad1, and so on. Black has a solid, but rather passive position, and the problematic c8-bishop is still there. } *[Event "?"]
