1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Be2 Ngf6 6. d3 e5 { A rare, but reasonable choice. Black is aiming to stabilize the centre and radically prevent further d3-d4 and e4-e5. } 7. a4 { As after 6...e6 White takes control of b5 square and makes a positional threat of a4-a5. } 7... Be7 ( { I've also examined } 7... b6 8. Nh4 { The most energetic - White's knight is heading on f5 and also unblocks the f-pawn. Black now struggles to complete the development of kingside pieces. } 8... g6 9. f4 Bg7 ( { In the event of } 9... Bb7 10. Nf3 Bg7 { White can favorably open the f-file } 11. fxe5 dxe5 { and then radically limit Black's active possibilities on the queenside with } 12. c4 $1 O-O 13. Nc3 { Black lacks any counterplay, and White's knight may effectively land on d5 at any moment. } ) 10. Qe1 { A flexible move. White protects the h4-knight and invites Black to show his cards. } 10... Bb7 ( { Careless is } 10... O-O $6 11. f5 d5 12. g4 { with massive attack on Black's monarch. } ) 11. f5 d5 { This is Black's only way to make counterplay. } 12. exd5 ( { Another interesting idea is } 12. Nc3 $5 d4 13. Nb1 { despite losing 2 tempi White reaches stability in centre and maintains excellent attacking prospects. } ) 12... Nxd5 13. Bf3 { Black's most active piece is neutralized now. } 13... Rb8 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Ne4 { Black's kingside is under strong pressure, especially in view of the upcoming Bc1-g5. } ) 8. Nc3 b6 ( { In the event of } 8... O-O 9. Nd2 Rb8 10. a5 { Black's pieces are rather cramped on the queenside, and then } 10... b5 11. axb6 Nxb6 12. Nc4 { [%csl Ra6,Rd6] leaves Black with no compensation for his inferior pawn structure. Palchuk, A - Razafindratsima, T Tornelo INT 2020 } ) ( { The prophylactic } 8... h6 { Buksa,N - Parol,P Warsaw 2021 can be naturally met with } 9. a5 $14 Nb8 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. Nc4 Be6 { Black builds his counterplay on attacking the a-pawn, but he will have to concess the bishop in order to capture it. } 12. f4 $1 { The most energetic. } 12... Bxc4 13. dxc4 Nxa5 14. Nd5 Nc6 15. Ra3 $36 { White's powerful bishops and structural defects make Black's position rather uncomfortable, although his is a pawn up. } ) 9. Nd2 Bb7 { Black declares his intent to play ...d6-d5 anytime soon. } ( 9... O-O 10. f4 exf4 11. Nc4 Ne5 12. Bxf4 Nxc4 13. dxc4 { also looks problematic for Black. } ) 10. Nc4 ( { The immediate } 10. f4 { is now not so effective because after } 10... exf4 11. Nc4 g5 $1 { Black manages to defend the pawn. } ) 10... O-O 11. f4 { Hardly there will be a better moment for initiating struggle on the kingside. } 11... exf4 12. Bxf4 d5 { Natural play by both players led to this position in Giri, A - Vachier Lagrave, M Stavanger 2016 Here the most consistent would be } 13. exd5 $14 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Bf3 Nf6 16. Bg3 { White's pieces are better coordinated. Black suffers from weak b6 and pressure along the f-file. } *[Event "?"]
