1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Be2 Ngf6 6. d3 b6 { This is a relatively modest way of development (compared to 6...b5) . Black is aiming to take more control of e4 and prevent ..d3-d4. } 7. c4 Bb7 8. Nc3 g6 { The most active choice. } ( { The alternative } 8... e6 { also allows White to quickly seize space on the kingside with f2-f4 } 9. Ne1 Be7 10. f4 O-O 11. Bf3 { In analogy to our main line, White places his bishop on the long diagonal, so ..e4-e5 is in the air. } 11... b5 $5 { This pawn sacrifice is the most challenging reaction to White's plan. } ( { In case of } 11... Ne8 12. Nc2 Nc7 13. a4 Rb8 ( { Too slow is } 13... Nb8 $6 { Schirmbeck,H - Schuh,P Austria 2019 } 14. d4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nc6 16. Be3 { Black's piece are poorly coordinated for traditional ''Hedgehog struggle'' } ) 14. Bd2 Ba8 15. Ne3 { Black is sort of stuck, since } 15... b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. cxb5 { makes it impossible to recapture on b5 because of Rxa8. } ) ( { The timid } 11... Qc7 $6 { allows White to quickly extend initiative with } 12. g4 Ne8 13. g5 g6 14. f5 $36 ) 12. Qe2 $1 { It is better for White to maintain the tension. } ( { After } 12. cxb5 axb5 13. Nxb5 d5 $44 { Black has some compensation a-la Benko gambit. } ) 12... b4 ( { After } 12... bxc4 13. dxc4 Qc7 14. Nd3 $14 { is hard to properly meet e4-e5. } ) 13. Nd1 Ne8 14. g4 { This closed middlegame offers interesting play for both sides, but I like White's attacking setup. } ) 9. Rb1 { It makes sense to put Black under some pressure on the b-file. } 9... Bg7 10. b4 Rb8 { The most reasonable way of covering the b7-bishop. This was Antipov,M - Grandelius,N Gjakova 2016Here I like the following flexible idea: } ( 10... Bc6 { took place in Moussard, J - Niemann, H Djerba 2024 In my opinion, White can claim some drawbacks of Black's last move by pushing ..d3-d4. Therefore, I find it logical to start with } 11. Qc2 $14 O-O 12. Rd1 Qc7 ( { Also after } 12... e6 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. d4 { Balck suffers from poor placement of light-squared bishop. } ) 13. Be3 Rac8 14. d4 { Hardly there will be a better moment to play this ambitious move. } 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 Bb7 16. Rbc1 { The standard Hedgehog position is favorable for White, who's pieces are well placed in centre and have targets (mostly b6) for an attack. } ) 11. h3 $14 O-O 12. Qc2 { White is ready to connect his rooks with Be3/f4/g5, depending on opponent's actions. } 12... Qc7 ( { After } 12... e6 13. Bf4 Qe7 14. Qd2 Ba8 15. a3 { White has the more harmonious setup when he can still prepare ..d3-d4, possibly after exchanging the dark-squared bishops. } ) 13. Bf4 e6 { Black covers d5 and declares his intent to play ...d6-d5 in the long run. } 14. Qd2 Bc6 15. a3 { The opposition along h2-b8 diagonal is quite annoying for Black, and ..d3-d4 is still in the air. } *[Event "?"]
