1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Be2 Ngf6 6. d3 e6 { This is Black's second choice after 6...g6. This way of development seems less ambitious than fianchetto, but Black takes more control of key d5-spot and it can potentially assist Black in playing ...d6-d5 in the long run. } 7. a4 { This move is aimed to limit Black's counterplay on the queenside, starting with b7-b5. } ( { After } 7. c4 b6 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Re1 Be7 10. h3 O-O 11. Bf4 Qc7 $13 { Black has no problems. Campora,D - Palac,M Lisbon 2017 } ) 7... b6 { The most natural reaction. Black reasonably prefers not to allow the squeezing a4-a5 and vacates b7 for the bishop. } ( { Black can also allow the ''squeezing'' a4-a5 and opt for a quick development with } 7... Be7 8. a5 O-O { The most natural. } ( { The attempt to attack the pawn by means of } 8... Nb8 $5 { is somewhat slow, and White can initiate favorable change of pawn structure: } 9. e5 Nd5 ( { Worse is } 9... dxe5 10. Nxe5 $14 ) 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Nbd2 { The knight is heading both on c4 and e4. } 11... Nc6 12. Nc4 Bc7 13. c3 O-O 14. Qa4 { Both sides have their merits, but I slightly prefer White's chances because of the superior pawn structure and clear target on c5. } ) 9. Re1 { White vacates f1 for the bishop's retreat and declares his intention to seize the centre with d3-d4 in the long run. } 9... b6 ( 9... Nb8 { diminishes White's control of e5, so } 10. e5 $1 dxe5 ( { Equally possible is } 10... Nd5 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12. Nc4 $14 ) 11. Nxe5 Nfd7 12. Nc4 { leaves Black's pieces crumped on the queenside. } ) ( { Black can also opt for ''waiting strategy'' with } 9... Qc7 10. Bf1 Re8 { , as in Ragger, M - Kraemer, M Germany 2024 Here the most consistent follow-up would be } 11. Nbd2 $14 Bf8 12. b3 { Black hardly has any other way to involve the c8-bishop except } 12... b5 13. axb6 Nxb6 14. e5 $14 { , but then White's pawn structure is much better. } ) 10. axb6 a5 { Black reasonably takes care of weak a-pawn. } ( { Less precise is } 10... Nxb6 11. Bd2 $1 { White fixes the weak a6-pawn. } 11... Bb7 12. Ba5 Nfd7 13. Nbd2 { the pin causes Black definite problems either. } ) ( { Or } 10... Qxb6 11. Na3 d5 12. Bf1 $14 { Black has to do with both ..exd5 and e4-e5. } ) 11. Na3 Nxb6 12. e5 { This a standard approach for such positions - White is interested in separating the c-pawn of the opponent. } 12... dxe5 13. Nxe5 Bb7 14. Bf3 { Black doesn't seem to have proper compensation for structural drawbacks. } ) 8. Nfd2 $5 { This somewhat unusual retreat is aimed to make f2-f4 possible. The positions that arise after f2-f4 are very similar to KID when Black's progress on the opposite side is usually less significant. There are all the pieces on the board, and it offers interesting play for both sides. } 8... Bb7 ( 8... Be7 9. f4 O-O { mostly transposes to 8...Bb7, but there can be an independent case too. } ( 9... Bb7 10. Bf3 { transposes to 8...Bb7 } ) 10. Nc3 { In my opinion, this move is the most precise. White develops his knight and temporarily prevents ...b6-b5. } ( 10. Bf3 { can be well met by } 10... Rb8 $5 ( { Instead, } 10... Bb7 { transposes to the main line in Nepomniatchi - Carlsen. } ) 11. g4 b5 12. g5 Ne8 { Black makes lots of progress on the queenside, and I am not sure if White's attacking prospects prevail. } ) 10... Rb8 { An ambitious approach: Black leaves the bishop on initial spot for a while and signals that b6-b5 is just to follow. } ( 10... Bb7 11. Bf3 { transposes to 8...Bb7. } ) ( { Anothjer possible transposition is } 10... Nb8 11. Bf3 Bb7 ) 11. Bf3 { White makes e2 vacant for the queen and takes more control of d5. } 11... b5 12. Qe2 b4 ( { After } 12... Qc7 13. g4 Ne8 14. Bg2 { White's initiative on the kingside is lasting much faster. } ) 13. Nd1 { White's setup is getting harmonious - the knight will be either placed on e3 or f2, and the queen's bishop is gonna be activated with b2-b3, Bc2-b2. } 13... d5 14. b3 { A decent move. White not only prepares fianchetto but also prevents Black from extending with c5-c4. } 14... Bb7 15. Bb2 Qc7 16. g3 { This position looks more pleasant for White, who has great attacking potential with further ..g3-g4. Black's only counter-attacking idea is c5-c4 break, but it is problematic. } ) 9. f4 Be7 10. Bf3 O-O ( 10... Qc7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. g4 { makes it easier for White to extend on the kingside. } 12... Nb8 13. g5 Nfd7 14. Bg2 { White unblocks both the f-file for his rook and diagonal for the queen. } 14... Nc6 15. Nc4 Nd4 { This position was reached in Baidetsky, V - Lagarde, M Zagreb 2023 Here I suggest the following approach: } 16. Ne2 b5 17. Ne3 f6 18. h4 { A complex struggle is ahead, but I like White's attacking prospects. } ) 11. Nc3 d5 { The most natural reaction. Opponent's aggressive actions are mostly met by break in centre. } ( { Somewhat artificial is } 11... Qb8 12. g4 b5 { This is the point - White cannot grab the pawn because Black's queen is keeping an eye on b5. } 13. g5 Ne8 14. Qe1 $14 { A flexible choice. White moves his queen towards g3 or h4 in order to connect the rooks. } ( 14. h4 b4 15. Ne2 d5 { led to a double-edged play in Juhasz, A - Grebnev, A Montesilvano 2023 } ) 14... f6 { Black is aiming to complicate the matters. } ( { After } 14... g6 15. b3 Ng7 16. Bb2 { White's setup looks more harmonious. } ) 15. g6 $5 { White sacrifices a pawn to prevent Black from activating his kingside pieces. } 15... hxg6 16. Qg3 { White has decent play on the g-file. } ) 12. g4 $1 Nb8 ( { After } 12... dxe4 13. dxe4 Qc7 14. Nc4 Rad8 15. Qe2 { White can do with the opening of the d-file because Black has no entry. On the other hand, Black has the inferior piece coordination. } ) ( 12... d4 13. Ne2 e5 14. g5 Ne8 15. h4 { looks like a standard KID struggle, when White's practical task is somewhat easier. } ) ( 12... h6 13. h4 d4 14. Ne2 Nh7 15. g5 { The most straightforward. } 15... hxg5 16. fxg5 $1 ( { The routine } 16. hxg5 e5 17. Nc4 exf4 { leads to unclear position, where both kings are in danger. } ) 16... Ne5 17. Bg2 { Despite Black's control over e5, I like White's chances because of poor h7-knight and decent play on the f-file. } ) 13. g5 Ne8 14. exd5 exd5 { We have been following the top-level game Nepomniachtchi, I - Carlsen, M Chess.com INT 2023 In my opinion, White could have make it much tougher for Black to develop the knight by means of } 15. Qe2 $14 Nc7 ( { The attempt to take over the initiative by means of } 15... Nc6 16. Nxd5 Nd4 17. Nxe7+ Kh8 { is interesting, but after } 18. Qg2 Nxf3+ 19. Nxf3 Qxe7 20. Qh3 { , followed by 21.f5 White can do with Black's strong bishop and Black's king is still unsafe. } ) 16. Qg2 b5 17. Nb3 { Black's central pawn is under strong pressure, so White's position is preferable. } *[Event "?"]
