1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Be2 Ngf6 6. d3 b5 { This is a risky, but quite ambitious response. From now ..Nb1-c3 looks less attractive for White in view of obvious ...b5-b4. On the downside, the b5-pawn turns a target for White's pieces, especially after White plays a2-a4. } 7. a4 b4 ( 7... Bb7 { is what was mostly tested in human games. Here I suggest the following new approach: } 8. d4 $14 { White is aiming to quickly open files against opponent's king and insist pressure on b5. } ( { After } 8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Qxa8 10. d4 Bxe4 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Bxb5 Bc6 { Black managed to consolidate and solve the major problems in Adams, M - Volokitin, A London 2023 } ) 8... cxd4 ( { White's development advantage prevails also in case of } 8... Bxe4 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. axb5 $36 ) 9. axb5 axb5 10. Rxa8 Bxa8 $1 { This is definitely the best. } ( 10... Qxa8 $6 { In analogy to Adams - Volokitin is much worse: } 11. Nxd4 b4 ( { Hardly better is } 11... Nxe4 12. Bxb5 e5 13. Re1 exd4 14. Qg4 $40 { with a powerful attack. } ) 12. Nb5 { The active b5-knight causes Black serious problems. } 12... Qc8 13. Bd2 $1 { Another decent resource. Black needs a few moves to complete development, so White has time to extend initiative on the queenside. } 13... Qc6 ( { After } 13... Nxe4 14. Bxb4 Qc6 15. f3 Qb6+ 16. Qd4 $36 { The queen's trade will not really solve Black's issues. } ) 14. f3 { A decent consolidating move. White can do with weakening g1-a7 diagonal. } 14... Qb6+ 15. Kh1 Bc6 16. c4 $36 { Black still struggles to complete development, and b4 is about to fall. } ) 11. Bxb5 { The pinned d7-knight causes Black serious problems from now. } 11... e5 { This is definitely the best - Black needs to unblock the bishop as soon as it possible. } ( { After } 11... Bxe4 $2 12. Nxd4 g6 13. Re1 Bg7 14. Bc6 { Black's position is nearly lost. } ) 12. c3 Be7 ( { Much worse is } 12... dxc3 $6 13. Nxc3 Be7 14. Nh4 O-O 15. Nf5 $36 { Activity of White's minor pieces and weak d6-pawn makes Black's position very dangerous. } ) 13. cxd4 { The major simplifications are invited. } 13... O-O ( { After } 13... exd4 14. Nxd4 O-O 15. Nf5 { White's bishop pair prevails. } ) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. f3 { Black doesn't seem to have full compensation for the pawn, even though his pieces are currently more active. } ) ( 7... Rb8 $6 { is a dubious attempt to keep the pawn chain flexible. } 8. axb5 axb5 9. Bd2 $1 Bb7 ( { Hardly better is } 9... Qc7 10. Ba5 Qb7 11. Na3 e6 12. d4 $36 ) 10. Ba5 Qc8 11. Nc3 Bc6 12. d4 $36 ) 8. c3 bxc3 { This best move hasn't been tried yet. } ( { Clearly worse is } 8... a5 $6 9. d4 $1 { White doesn't fear of losing the central pawn - the development advantage prevails. } 9... cxd4 ( { After } 9... Nxe4 10. Re1 Nef6 { Black wastes a few more tempi, so } 11. Bg5 e6 12. Bb5 $36 { yiels White a powerful initiative. } ) 10. Nxd4 $1 { White activates his knight with a great effect. } 10... Bb7 11. cxb4 axb4 12. Bb5 { Black suffers from weak b4-pawn and lack of development. Rohde,F-Watson,R LSS email 2014 } ) 9. Nxc3 e5 { The safest way. Black restricts his dark-squared bishop but radically prevents d3-d4. } ( { After } 9... Bb7 10. Rb1 $1 { Black struggles to properly meet b2-b4 } 10... e6 11. b4 cxb4 12. Rxb4 Rb8 13. Be3 { White's development advantage is very significant - Black has to do with the threat of 14.Ba7. } ) 10. a5 Be7 11. Nh4 $1 { White reasonably starts actions on the kingside now, when Black's king is still in centre. } 11... Nb8 ( 11... g6 { is very committing. } 12. f4 O-O 13. f5 $36 { Black's king feels exposed. } ) 12. Nf5 Bxf5 { Black cannot do with such an active knight. However, it costs him concessing the strong bishop. } 13. exf5 Nc6 14. Bf3 Rc8 15. Bg5 { This position is evaluated as almost equal by engines. but White's practical task looks easier because of control over light squares and some prospects with an extension on the kingside with g2-g4. } *[Event "?"]
