1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Be2 Ngf6 6. d3 g6 7. c4 Bg7 { This is the most common and natural move. On the downside, after 8.Nc3 Black's counter-attacking actions with ...b7-b5 are problematic. } 8. Nc3 { [%cal Gd3d4] } 8... O-O ( 8... Ne5 $6 { is a dubious attempt to deviate from Marocy type of positions. } 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Be3 Qd6 { This was Roiz,M - Aizenberg,B Israel 2024 Now the simple } 11. Rb1 $14 O-O 12. b4 cxb4 13. c5 { would have put Black in a difficult situation because White's play on the queenside is lasting itself. } ) ( 8... b6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bb7 11. f3 O-O 12. Bg5 Rc8 ( { After } 12... h6 13. Be3 Rc8 14. Qd2 Kh7 15. Rfd1 $14 { Whtie gains an important tempo by attacking h6 and reaches a harmonious Mrocy setup, when Black's counterplay is questionable. } ) 13. Qd2 Rc5 14. Be3 { White was firmly in control in Balakrishnan, P - Gutla, A Chesterfield 2023 } ) ( { After } 8... e5 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 b6 11. Rb1 { White has somewhat more space and the c3-knight is superior over the d7-knight. } ) 9. d4 cxd4 ( { In the event of } 9... e6 { White can clarify the situation in the centre by means of } 10. dxc5 $5 Nxc5 ( { Worse is } 10... dxc5 $6 11. Qd6 Re8 12. Rd1 { Black struggles to complete development of queenside pieces. } ) 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. Be3 Bc6 13. Nd2 { There are many pieces on the board, so White's space development feels significant. } ) 10. Nxd4 Nc5 ( { Hardly better is } 10... Qc7 11. Be3 e6 12. Rc1 b6 { Black manages to complete development, but the arising middlegame a-la Hedgehog is uncomfortable because Black's queenside pawns are vulnerable. } 13. f3 Bb7 14. Qd2 Rac8 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. b4 { Black's counterplay with ...d6-d5 is questionable. At the same time, White has few promising ideas on the queenside such as Nd4-b3, followed by a2-a4-a5. } ) 11. f3 Qb6 ( { Very commtting is } 11... e5 12. Nc2 Ne6 13. a4 Nf4 { A temporary activity. } 14. Rf2 Nxe2+ 15. Rxe2 { Black has no compensation for weak d6-pawn and passive fianchettoed bishop. Moriarty, A - Wilkinson, J ICCF email 2020 } ) ( 11... Bd7 12. Be3 Rb8 13. Qd2 Ne6 { was played by a few strong players, including GM Anish Giri. Black is relying on ...b7-b5 break, but after } 14. Rfd1 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 b5 16. e5 $1 { White takes advantage of his superior piece coordination. A likely continuation is } 16... dxe5 17. Bxe5 b4 18. Nd5 { Black gets under strong pressure along the d-file. } ) 12. Kh1 Ne6 ( { Possibly, it makes sense for Black to swap the knights by means of } 12... Bd7 13. Rb1 Na4 14. Nxa4 Bxa4 15. b3 Bc6 16. Be3 $14 { , but still White has decent prospects with further extension on the queenside. Szpar, M - Ouellet,M Seville 2024 } ) 13. Nc2 $1 { Following the well-known concept: If you have a space advantage - avoid simplifications! Black's knight is placed awkwardly on c6, while White's knight can be transferred to d5 very soon. } 13... Bd7 14. Rb1 { White isn't in a rush. This move isn't only prophylactic: the further b2-b4 advance is gonna be promising. } 14... Qa5 15. Be3 Rfc8 16. b4 Qd8 17. Nd5 { White has reached the maximum for Marocy: Black's pieces are cramped, and the exchange on d5 will increase White's space advantage. Karthikeyan, M - Sethuraman,S chess24.com INT 2022 } *[Event "?"]
