1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Be2 Ngf6 6. d3 { This modest-looking move is White's top choice by far. Currently, the e2-bishop is blocked, but White still intends to push d3-d4 at the proper moment. White's strategic plan is based on the somewhat awkward placement of d7-knight that often makes it tough for Black to push d6-d5. } ( 6. Nc3 { was proved as harmless in practice. Indeed, after } 6... b5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bb7 { Black reaches a harmonious setup a-la Najdorf with lots of counterplay against e4. } ) 6... g6 7. c4 b5 { Quite an aggressive choice. Black is trying to interrupt White's plan that clearly involves ..d3-d4 advance. } ( 7... b6 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Rb1 Bg7 10. b4 { transposes to 6...b6. } ) ( 7... Nb8 { is a natural attempt to relocate the knight on c6. It hasn't been tried yet. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d4 Bg4 { Black is trying to occupy d4. } ( { After } 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bg7 11. Be3 { Black has an inferior version of Marocy, when a7-a6 may backfire as it weakens b6. } ) 10. d5 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nd4 { The knight has reached its destination but isn't stable. } 12. Be3 Nxf3+ ( { After } 12... Bg7 13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 O-O 15. Qd2 Nd7 16. Be2 { Black doesn't seem to have full compensation for a pawn, although his bishop is very strong. } ) 13. Qxf3 Bg7 14. Qe2 O-O 15. a4 { White has a traditional space advantage with f2-f4 to follow soon. } ) 8. cxb5 $1 { White has to open files and diagonals to challenge Black's last move. } ( 8. Nc3 { was played in a couple of games, but it is less effective: } 8... bxc4 9. dxc4 Bg7 { looks roughly equal. } ) 8... axb5 9. d4 $1 { This move is especially attractive now when Black's development has been delayed. Black is at a crossroads now. } 9... cxd4 { This is what was played practically in all the games so far. } ( 9... c4 { runs into } 10. Nc3 $1 b4 11. Nb5 Nb6 { We have been following the game Remizov, Y - Kobalia,M Obninsk 2022Here I find the most energetic } ( { After } 11... Nxe4 12. Bxc4 Bg7 13. Re1 { White has a free initiative. } ) 12. b3 $14 c3 ( { After } 12... cxb3 13. Qxb3 Bg7 14. Bd3 O-O 15. Qxb4 { Black doesn't have much for the pawn. } ) ( { Nearly the same can be said about } 12... Nxe4 13. bxc4 Bg7 14. Qb3 O-O 15. Qxb4 ) 13. d5 { White's main idea is 14.Qd4, and then the b4-pawn will fall. } 13... Nxe4 14. Nfd4 { White's knight land on c6 with a great effect. Black's position is very difficult. } ) 10. Nxd4 Nxe4 ( 10... Bb7 11. Bxb5 Nxe4 { is another possible moves order. } ) 11. Bxb5 Bb7 { This is practically forced in view of 12.Bc6 threat. } 12. Nd2 $14 { This natural developing move is a novelty. White is interested in exchanging the most active piece of the opponent. } 12... Nxd2 ( { After } 12... Nf6 13. b4 Bg7 14. Bb2 Rc8 15. Rc1 { Black is under strong pressure in view of upcoming..Nc6 - after exchange of b7-bishop White's passerts will become especially powerful. } ) 13. Bxd2 Bg7 14. Bc3 { It makes sense to neutralize the opponent's strong fianchettoed bishop. } ( 14. Be3 $5 { is worth attention either. } ) 14... O-O { Black has nothing else left. } 15. Nc6 Bxc6 16. Bxc6 { The bishop i usually superior over the knight is much unbalanced positions. } 16... Rc8 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qd4+ Kg8 19. Rfc1 { It is easier for White to advance the queenside passers because Black's pieces are not well-mobilized for supporting the central pawns. } *[Event "?"]
