1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O e6 { This is the most common among Black's deviations from the main lines. } ( 4... g6 5. Re1 Bg7 6. c3 Nf6 7. d4 { transposes to 4...Ngf6 side. } ) ( 4... e5 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 Be7 7. d4 { tranposes to 4...Ngf6 side. } ) ( 4... Qb6 $6 { is a dubious attempt to enter unexplored paths. Here I mostly like } 5. Qe2 $14 { White keeps c2-c3 as an option. } ( { Instead, } 5. Nc3 e6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 a6 8. Be2 Ngf6 { led to standard middglegame a-la Najdorf in Estimo,S-Larsen,B Bauang 1973 } ) 5... Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Ba4 e6 8. d4 { White achieved his goal, and Kd8-b6 turns useless. } ) 5. Re1 Ne7 { This way of development makes a strange impression and hardly can be recommended. } ( 5... a6 6. Bf1 Ngf6 { transposes to 4...Ngf6. } ) 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 ( 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bc2 Ng6 9. d4 Bb7 { is less promising, in my opinion. } ) 7... d5 8. e5 ( { Another decent option is } 8. exd5 $5 Nxd5 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 { Black faces difficulties with developing king-side pieces. Also, the c8-bishop } ) 8... Nc6 9. d4 b5 { This was Fernandez Siles, L - Maghsoodloo, P Chess.com INT 2022 White can choose between a few good-looking possibilities, such as } 10. dxc5 $14 { It yields White access to d4-square. } 10... Bxc5 11. Nbd2 Qb6 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Nb3 { Black's king feels potentially exposed when all Black's pieces are located on the opposite side. } *[Event "?"]
